The case is straightforward enough but I am placed in an awkward

dilemma, if I adopt the line of defence which the opposite side expect, ,

because I have not only to speak against an old and valued friend but, what is more unpleasant, to institute a comparison between him and my client in respect to personal merits, seeing that Laterensis insists upon my showing what stronger claim Plancius had to the aedileship than himself, and so I must either admit the superiority of Laterensis claim to the injury of my client, or else wound his susceptibilities (§§ 5, 6).
